TL;DR

The objective of this analysis is to see whether our fee change on October 23, 2020 (from 1% to 3% on recurring Stripe topup transactions) affected customer funding behavior. The overall answer is it most likely did not, which implies there this funding method is relatively price inelastic.

  • Theres no confirmed change to the Signup -> second deposit rate
    • However, directionally it appears users are now more likely to make a second deposit
  • There was no significant change to total deposits within 14 days of KYC Complete
    • Its possible after the fee change were seeing smaller topup amounts per txn, but more transactions per user
  • Lapse rates might have improved
    • There arent enough users for statistical significance, and due to the large amount of time required between cohorts in this part of the pre/post analysis additional external factors could influence lapse rates
  • Recurring TopUp transactions are ~2 points less risky now than recurring txns before the fee change

Takeaways and Recommendation

THIS WAS NOT AN A/B TEST. All outputs should be taken with a grain of salt (see the Caveats section).

We project were currently making about $2,500/month on Stripe topup right now, counting both first and recurring deposits. Theres an estimated margin of $0.40 per transaction, making for an ~16% total margin. Combined with the fact that we dont see a change in user behavior when it comes to funding or total amounts funded (despite low numbers in the analysis) we can likely leave fee pricing where it is and move on to optimizing other funding methods. For more detail on the dollar cost and revenue of running this feature so far, see this document.

Caveats

All analysis here was done as a pre/post analysis. The lapse rate analysis was underpowered because not enough time has passed since the fee change. Whenever we do a pre/post analysis we risk being influenced by a variety of external factors, including but not limited to:

  • changes in market sentiment
  • differences between cohorts
  • changes to the unemployment rate (unfortunately a major factor this year)
  • changes in fraudulent user behavior (we filtered out all confirmed fraud cases, but we might not have caught all of it)
  • marketing/acquisition efforts that happened at different periods
  • etc
